        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1970-09-09T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1970-09-09T00:00:00-05:00" n="291"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d291">
                <head>291. Note From the Presidentʼs Assistant for National Security Affairs
                        (<persName corresp="#p_KHA1" type="from">Kissinger</persName>) to President
                        <persName corresp="#p_NRM1" type="to">Nixon</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d291fn1">Source: National Archives, <persName
                            corresp="#p_NRM1">Nixon</persName> Presidential Materials, <gloss
                            target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Files, Box 593, Country Files, Middle East,
                        Greece, Vol. I, Jan 69–Oct 70. No classification marking.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1970-09-09">September 9, 1970</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="flushleft">Mr. President:</p>
                <p>In view of the Middle East situation<note n="2" xml:id="d291fn2">On August 26
                        fighting broke out between Palestinian and Jordanian forces. Beginning on
                        September 6, a series of Western airliners were seized by terrorists and
                        flown to Jordan where the crews and passengers were held hostage. See <ref
                            target="frus1969-76ve01#d45">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1969–1976, volume E–1,
                            Documents on Global Issues, 1969–1972, Document 45</ref>.</note> this is
                    an ideal time to proceed rapidly with the announcement of resumption of <gloss
                        target="#t_US1">U.S.</gloss> military assistance to Greece. It will also
                    assist in creating a favorable climate in the event we have to call on Greek
                    cooperation should a contingency occur.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Henry A. Kissinger</hi>
                        </persName>
                        <note n="3" xml:id="d291fn3">Printed from a copy that bears this typed
                            signature.</note>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
